<Layout title="Home">
  <p class="positioning">
    I'm an independent AI researcher and consultant specializing in how
    artificial intelligence is transforming information threats — and how
    to defend against them.
  </p>

  <p>
    My PhD, from National Cheng Kung University in Taiwan, is in artificial
    intelligence. My research and publication record focuses on using AI to
    defend against information threats — probing what language models
    actually understand, and applying that to detecting manipulation and
    deception at scale.
  </p>

  <p>
    My current work sits at the sharp edge of that problem. I'm contributing
    to a robust methodology for detecting AI-assisted grooming behavior, tracking
    how AI is changing the tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) behind
    information threats, and examining how kill-chain analysis frameworks
    need to be rethought for an AI-augmented threat landscape. I'm also
    researching the cutting-edge capabilities being developed by adversaries,
    by studying the AI research literature and patents coming out of known
    threat actors.
  </p>

  <p>
    I've also built AI systems for real deployments: contributing the AI
    component to Freedom House's China Dissent Monitor, which identifies
    offline protests inside the People's Republic of China from Weibo
    posts, and building a product for researchers connected to the Ukraine
    government analysing PRC-linked information threats to Ukraine.
  </p>

  <p>
    That work grew out of several years in the NGO sector, where I held
    roles as Research Scientist, Research Lead, and eventually Deputy CEO at
    Doublethink Lab, overseeing delivery of research projects exceeding USD
    $10M in funding from partners including the European Union, Open Society
    Foundation, National Endowment for Democracy, German Ministry of Foreign
    Affairs, UK FCDO, Global Affairs Canada, the Global Engagement Center,
    Freedom House, Friedrich Naumann Foundation, and Internews. That work
    was recognised as world-leading in the region and featured in The Wall
    Street Journal, The Washington Post, The Guardian, and Le Monde.
  </p>

  <p>
    A core part of my time at Doublethink Lab was spent building coalitions
    across the Indo-Pacific — connecting civil society, academia, and
    government around shared frameworks, methodologies, and data formats —
    enabling intelligence sharing and coordinated regional response. Having
    done too many "autopsies" on information threats, I've come to see
    effective response and mitigation, with coordination at its core, as the
    more urgent challenge now.
  </p>

  <p>
    I'm now independent, bringing that research and delivery experience to
    AI-focused research and advisory work on information threats.
  </p>
</Layout>
